text: I call BS. I wish this wasn't so unrealistic. Great white sharks only breach near seal island and in false bay which are both located in South Africa. There has never been a reported sighting of a shark breaching in Australia. Also, if a shark did attack one of the guys swimming, then they almost certainly would not have attacked the second guy, let alone chase him down to the rock. Great white sharks have very, very sensitive teeth, as soon as they bite into you and realize that you do not have the fat density that they need for their diet (like a seal), they usually lose interest except for in cases of extreme hunger. A shark would never, never wait around a rock waiting for a person to jump in the water. The shark would have swam away within minutes of the first attack.

text: Just when you thought it was safe... to go more than two feet back into the water.  I can already imagine the sequel, with a new camouflage patterned ray-like shark that hides under the sand, bites into anyone that gets ankles deep or higher, and drags them beneath the sea-foam. Even calm walks on the beach become impossible, as people who so much as dip their feet in disappear one by one. Eventually, the president orders a military blockade set up between the shore and the water, leaving a few unlucky survivors trapped on the other side. If they try to cross, they will be electrocuted. Now, with a bombing strike on the beach 48 hours away and high tide imminent, these strangers must band together in the worst game of "Hot Lava" ever to overcome this nightmare. Their one goal: Kill or be killed.   Get ready for the ultimate in slightly underwater terror, from Quentin Tarantino, The Shallows 2: Under Toe

text: As someone who has surfed their entire life, all you can do is laugh at this! Yeah, sharks are in the ocean, but they certainly don't outright "hunt" humans like this. I've been surfing in California, Hawaii, and the South Pacific and seen great whites, tiger sharks, and a variety of reef sharks. If this were to happen in real life it would be as follows: 1) shark sees Blake Lively from underwater and thinks she is a seal 2) shark bites Lively, realizes she is not a seal, and swims away in search of a seal 3) Lively waits 10-15 minutes on the rock before shark is gone and swims to shore 4) Lively most likely dies as a result of the poor medical facilities on a remote island OR by getting hit on the head with a coconut, since falling coconut accidents cause more deaths per year than shark attacks.  Long story short, sharks don't really care about humans. It would be so refreshing if Hollywood put money into a film that actually told an authentic story about women and surfing, versus a film that put illegitimate fears into people.

text: This movie is called "The Shallows" Yet the shark that is being used is a Great White. Great Whites don't venture in shallow water- they are too big. Second off why in the Bloody Hell would a Great White go after humans like that?! A diet of humans is ethical for a Great Whites; we are too boney and take too long to digest- they prefer the easier to digest protein filled blubber of Seals and Sea Lions.  Now I know "it's just a movie and not meant to be accurate". Problem is there is only so much disbelief one can except, and this trailer has exceeded it, not to mention the Great Whites are overused and don't deserve all the fear. You want shark that deserves to be feared more and can swim in shallow water? Well there are two: the Tiger Shark and the Bull Shark.

text: Hear's how they should've done this movie. It's just Livelu's character, no explaining how she got on the rock or what. There is minimal dialogue. The shark is not actively seeking her out but everytime she tries to swim to shore, it catches the scent of the blood from her leg and goes after. She does not go Rambo on the shark. It becomes on Observation of how someone would react and adapt in a situation like that, similar to like, All is Lost or Buried. There should also be some shots that show that the shark is just that... a shark. It's not evil or cruel or malicious, its just an animal trying to find food and survive. Add ambiguous ending and bam... movie!

text: Well, I want to see it but it looks FUCKING SCARY.  I was terrified of sharks after seeing "Jaws" as a kid (and, no, you SJWs out there, I didn't turn into Captain Quint and start "slaughtering" them because they were scawy).  That effect of the surfer being eaten was STUNNING and biologically accurate in terms of how GWS hunt.  Deep Blue Sea was all CGI and had some fun parts but was ultimately hokey.  This looks like a great movie from an effects perspective.  That said, a GWS is so stupid that you could probably just swim to shore and be fine.  After all, you swam out and were fine, right?  Anyway, if you have ever seen "The Reef" you can get an idea of just how uncomfortable these types of movies can be...

text: I don't think it matters what you see in the trailer as this movie clearly has a larger message about what human beings are doing to sharks, robbing them of their food source and forcing them closer to shore. This leads me to think the main concept behind this movie is about the consequences of doing this to such an active and dangerous predator. The people making the movie only show you a number of money shots, of which there will probably be more action than you think you've seen, to get your attention and highlight the premise of the film. The basic premise that she is stuck on the water despite being close to shore is probably the scariest notion the trailer portrays, the idea of being so close to safety from the threat, yet so far. There is probably a larger psychological(-torture) plot behind this movie than an idiotic film like *shudders* Sharknado, much like Jaws. Therefore I think in my opinion, which in the grand scheme of the internet is like a whisper in a hall full of yelling and you can ignore, you should definitely see this potentially intelligent and environmentally aware film, learn from it and support its makers and message (intended or not) because there is more to it if you have the basic intelligence required to look. **On a separate note, trailers are supposed to make you buy the ticket to the movie, and often what you interoperate from a trailer is not what the movie is actually about. Eg, Civil War took me by surprise at several points (not really a spoiler, but yeah) so judging a movie off a trailer and saying "I've basically seen the movie now" is kind of ignorant and presumptuous on your part, because trailers are in a way another form of delivering media and entertainment and sometimes have branching plots, concepts and intended messages in the same manner of books and book-films. But by all means chase the self-satisfied feeling your getting by thinking you are superior or intelligent by saying "I've seen everything", and feel free to be offended by my assessment of your satisfaction from saying this kind of thing.
author: David Clarke

text: I don't think it matters what you see in the trailer as this movie clearly has a larger message about what human beings are doing to sharks, robbing them of their food source and forcing them closer to shore. This leads me to think the main concept behind this movie is about the consequences of doing this to such an active and dangerous predator. The people making the movie only show you a number of money shots, of which there will probably be more action than you think you've seen, to get your attention and highlight the premise of the film. The basic premise that she is stuck on the water despite being close to shore is probably the scariest notion the trailer portrays, the idea of being so close to safety from the threat, yet so far. There is probably a larger psychological(-torture) plot behind this movie than an idiotic film like *shudders* Sharknado, much like Jaws. Therefore I think in my opinion, which in the grand scheme of the internet is like a whisper in a hall full of yelling and you can ignore, you should definitely see this potentially conceptually intelligent and environmentally aware film, learn from it and support its makers and message (intended or not) because there is more to it if you have the basic intelligence required to look, when its so much easier to be negative. **On a separate note, trailers are supposed to make you buy the ticket to the movie, and often what you interoperate from a trailer is not what the movie is actually about. Eg, Civil War took me by surprise at several points (not really a spoiler, but yeah) so judging a movie off a trailer and saying "I've basically seen the movie now" is kind of ignorant and presumptuous on your part, because trailers are in a way another form of delivering media and entertainment and sometimes have branching plots, concepts and intended messages in the same manner of books and book-films. But by all means chase the self-satisfied feeling your getting by thinking you are superior or intelligent by saying "I've seen everything", and feel free to be offended by my assessment of your satisfaction from saying this kind of thing.

text: This movie looks very good and I planned on seeing it—but can't the companies trust the material enough to NOT put the huge moments and scares right into the trailer?! Now I know when she's going to be attacked and when she's not. I know exactly what happens to the two surfer dudes. I know she gets off the reef and to the buoy. I know she uses something on the buoy to probably kill the shark. I mean, Jesus, these are major moments in this movie and we know them thoroughly now. Really disappointing. I think you'll find, Sony, that you can sell movies with very limited revelations. People who see this type of film want to be scared to death, they want to be surprised, they want to experience suspense. You've really done a disservice to your film and its potential audience with a trailer like this.

text: I would be ecstatic if this movie had an original story line.  I would be super excited if this movie had stunning effects and gripping and relate able characters.  I would be happy to see this movie, if I hadnt seen Jaws years before this started production.    I want to go into the film business self-taught and I wanna direct movies that will (hopefully) make it big.  For me to do that, I have been watching and critiquing movies based on its use of effects to progress the story, a compelling story, and characters we can relate to and base ourselves on.    But this movie.  This movie is a clear and blatant rip off of the classic movie Jaws.  Sure, you can argue that this is a different plot, and a lot of things are different, but look at the overall characters, and the whole plot in general.  Hell, a lot of the scenes in this trailer alone clearly mimic classic scenes from Jaws.  The blood in the water,  yelling out "SHARK!"  to alert the people, swimmers being drug into the ocean by an unknown force, and of course, that gun shot.  I can get if this movie would be a sequel to the Jaws movies, or a homage to that franchise, but this trailer shows otherwise.  I would suggest to the people who think that this movie looks great and original to go watch the first Jaws movie, and then relate this trailer to that movie.  The results and similarities are quite stunning and non-coincidental.  I urge you to see that movie first before you see this one.

The tourista board  of that area was warned to shut down the beach but kept it open to make money.  .... Nah, none of all that. text: You know what's weird, Hollywood keeps making movies about killer sharks, making people think that they are vicious man eaters. But sharks don't purposely attack people, it's usually a case of mistaken identity or curiosity. Sharks rarely attack humans, and very rarely kill them. Statistically you're more likely to die from mosquitos, bees, ants, lightning, ladders, dogs, hippos, autoerotic asphyxiation, falling out of bed, cows, falling coconuts, or vending machines. Yeah, sharks kill fewer people per year than coconuts, cows and vending machines. A true man eater (Sarcasm level=over 9000).

text: okokokokokokokokok FIRST OF ALL, the size of that shark is bigger than roughly an average great white, other than the issue with size, Great whites aren't typically found in shallow waters. More commonly, you'd find a black or white tip reef sharp, which is significantly smaller and has identifiable black tips on its fins and tail (vise vera for white tip). OR MAYBE a mako, but even then, a mako is much slimmer than that. Not only is this VERY inaccurate, it also depicts sharks as vicious evil monsters. Which is: A. Not original, and B. not true. Sharks would not eat a person unless they had to or unless they mistook them for a seal. Not to mention, the shark would not wait that long for the girl to come down, it would find another source of food. Just saying........

text: Looks entertaining, but realistically, would a shark really hang around that long just to stalk its (hard to get) prey? I find it frustrating how in so many giant-monster-animal-thing movies (like Anaconda, King Kong, some movie about giant spiders, etc.) the predator always kills its prey, barely eats it, and just throws it away to kill more... that's not how animals act. They kill to eat and for defense, not for pure spite.  Anyway, side rant over, this looks pretty good in my opinion, aside from the weird ogre growl the shark lets out when it first jumps out of the water.

text: Jaws: Small town with plenty of people during a hot summer. Nobody's safe because a large shark is apparently feeding near the shore. There are plenty of characters ranging from kids to adults, from sunbathers to laypersons, from marine experts to fishermen, and a heavy emphasis on community. I can relate to a few of them because I go to the beach sometimes, especially during the summer when it's full of people.  The trailer to The Shallows displays no such sense of relatability. Never been to some secluded "paradise" island. Not a surfer myself. Could be a fun film, but most likely not something I'd pay for, specifically because if I can't put myself in the characters' shoes, the dread factor doesn't exist.

text: As impressive and intense as this film looks, I wish we'd quit persisting with the "fear sharks, they kill people" theme. Sharks are more frequently killed by people than the opposite ("For every human killed by a shark, humans kill two million sharks": http://natgeotv.com/ca/human-shark-bait/facts ). They're ocean predators and wild animals. They aren't going to seek you out to kill you. This movie looks super thrilling but let's not forget to educate ourselves and treat these big, beautiful animals with respect! They are considered "vulnerable" on the endangered list!  Or who knows, maybe the shark in this film turns out to save the girl...wouldn't that be something :)

text: Ok just a tip for those who god forbid, ever get bitten by a shark. The best advice one can give is don't panic, but I think that's a bit of out of reach suggestion. So, in order to minimise the risk of getting attacked again swim away slowly. Don't kick your arms and legs as Blake is doing here, that only tells the shark, along with your heart rate, that you're a frightened prey. Slowly paddle your hands like a dog, making sure you keep your eyes on the shark at all times. Never turn your back. And always have something with which to defend yourselves. Hope none of you ever find yourselves in such a situation! Stay safe.

On the beach in a one piece bathing suit,shirt,hat. As others kind of look at her. A young man in a arm cast, run up to her with a smile and ask her if she is one of the judges in the,surf contest. Jenny,don't know what to say at first. Hey! I'm Johnny and this is my sister,Mila,she'll be in the contest. She great. No said Jenny,I'm here to study plants. Well I'm a surfer,but I also grow many plants,I'm good at both. My friend's call me Pockco. (Jenny smiles.) My sister and I are walking to get a bite to eat,come on along and tell me what plants you like. During the summer Jenny is amazed at how much Johnny knows about plants. Slowly,what happens when you meet the right person at the perfect time in life. Jenny go out surfing daily. People back home are SHOCK!,this can't be Jenny the nerd. They either do it if they're starving, if they mistake you for something else (such as a seal), or they are curious. Usually when sharks attack humans they bite once or twice then they leave (pro science skills right here). Plus, the shark could have easily gotten on that rock by jumping or just flop on to the rock. And to avoid a shark biting you twice, rip it's gills with your hand, hit it in the nose, or rip it's eyes.

text: What a retarded plot, this is why sharks have such a bad reputation when in reality they kill fewer people than fridge's do each year.  The shark depicted here is so unrealistically big is makes me sick.  Humans kill upwards of 100 million sharks per year, which means we kill more sharks per hour than sharks kill people in an entire year (10-15).  Sharks are docile animals that just want to mind their own business most of the time.  They are extremely important to marine ecosystems and at the rate we are killing them off, they will be extinct in no time.  Without sharks marine ecosystems, that we rely on for food, tourism etc. will die off.  Stupid movies like this only exasperate the problem, don'y understand the point.  Why not just make up some mythical creature instead of giving a real animal a bad reputation.

text: I do love the movie, I've seen it, but it was a bit unrealistic. How the shark stayed for her, and how it kept eating humans. Sharks hate the taste of humans, and they sometimes think they're seals, and when they realise they aren't, they spit them out, sometimes swallow them, or take a piece from them. So why would the shark stay for her? Also, I think she was there for 2-3 days, and if it was three days then how did she survive through the whole movie with no clean water and only attempting to eat a crab, only to throw it up? Unless that shark was starving, I don't think it would be eating humans and attacking them unprovoked (unless he thought they were seals, perhaps) But it is just a movie, I may be thinking about it too much, but it was a great movie

author: Fabian Thiel

text: Yet another movie that invokes fear and hatred of sharks. Sharks are and extremely important part of marine ecosystems, and humans are bringing them to extinction. Instead of creating fear about these animals, the media should be spreading information and facts about them in order to teach the masses about these fish. The people should learn to respect them, and want to protect them from human-driven extinction, instead of fearing them through ignorance and stupidity. In 2015 there were 98 shark attacks worldwide with only 6 deaths. Instead, people kill roughly 190 sharks worldwide per minute. Shark attacks may be on the rise, but only because we as humans are destroying their ecosystems and habitats, warming their oceans and depleting their food resources. The only monsters we should be worried about are ourselves, and what we should really be worrying about is how to stop ourselves from destroying our oceans, not about the "terrible monster that will kill you and your family, lurking just under the water waiting to kill you because that's what sharks do and their purpose in life is to kill you for fun".

text: Blake Lively has nine lives in this film i swear a God. This was just so freaking dopey, ridiculous, non intelligent, cartoonish and not in a good way. Huge problem here is that this film takes itself deadly serious, when in reality it is closer to SYFY original. You really need to suspend your disbelief for the majority of the film and in the end it just goes down quicker than shark chasing  Blake to the bottom. Yes, the perfromance by Blake Lively was convincing and movie looks great, production is top notch, it is fast paced short film but in the end it is cornball. It is goofy and cheap, honestly you do not care if the shark eats her, characters make stupid decisions and in the end this whole movie felt like someone tried to make a quick buck without making cohesive and smart chiller. 2/5

text: I saw 'The Shallows' last week and thought it was a thoroughly decent movie, I just wish they would've reworked it to be 'Jaws 5: The Shallows', now you might disagree but just hear me out.  First of all the film is obviously greatly influenced by 'Jaws' so it wouldn't actually need much reworking, just rewrite Lively's character as Thea Brody (the Brody's granddaughter from the 4th film) with her deceased mother therefore becoming Carla Brody and relocate the final scene from Galveston to Amity Island with cameos from Lorraine Gary and Dennis Quaid/Lance Guest, the film itself essentially remains the same, add John Williams' inimitable theme and you have the best 'Jaws' film since the first!

text: I really enjoyed this film because as per usual I don't listen to people who are Paid To Criticize...  They should try creating something instead of moaning about other people's music/movies & books et al  Seriously who stood up in class as a Kid & said " I want to become a Critic! " So Sad...  That's aside with any movie you have to leave your brain at the door to a certain degree as even True Story Films have content in them that never happens but it pads out the movie & if done properly adds more layers to the narrative without taking too many liberties when it is in fact a true story... I'm not saying The Shallows is based on a True Story I'm just adding that films whether fiction or fact need (at times) scenes that keep the movie ticking along...  I was glad to see that the shark was not seen as a mindless killing machine & it was in fact like many real shark attacks it's been humun(s) that have strayed into their territory & this movie clearly shows (without giving anything away) that the shark in question was challenging anything that would come close to the dead whale as sharks predominately feast on rich blubber from whales & again this movie doesn't try to tell you that the character has found this out too late as you see this for yourself onscreen...  I enjoyed the way the character opened up about her life & though she would fight til the end I'm guessing she knew she wouldn't make it back to shore...  I remember my Dad taking me to see Jaws when it was first released in 1975 & being only 8 years young I was absolutely fascinated with the ocean especially great white sharks/orcas/architeuthis & other giant squids & marine biology in general but after watching Jaws I knew my life had been changed & I'd still look to the skies but the inner space of the ocean holds far more valuable information that could/maybe one day eradicate many illnesses like Cancer/Aids/Parkinson/MS/Fibromyalgia & M.E just to name a few but we shouldn't just take from the ocean but conserve the lives of all who live & thrive in oceans of this world also...  Any way my main gripe is not of this movie but about Content overall that comes with DVD's & Blu Ray Films or should I now say Lack Of Content...  For those old enough to remember the advent of Films from VHS/Laserdisc & then  on to DVD it was not only better visually but you had hours of added extras in the way of Behind The Scenes/Blooper Reel & much much more & more often than not you had hours of visualing pleasure & information about the movie & even separate parts predominately about the subject matter of that film but for the last 15 years & then with Blu Ray we have saw DVD Film's go from being jam packed with content about that particular movie & it started to get less & less & I thought with Blu Ray it would pick up again with in film content but No it's just as bad & your lucky if you get a few 5 minutes worth of extras!..  I can understand why Big Studios were at first against Films on Video Format but instead of taking away revenue it added it & many movies became cult classics via Video like John Carpenters remake of " The Thing " as that (excuse my wording) bombed in the cinemas & was one of his first badly recieved movies in the cinema as it was just too out there & gory but time has shown that it found it's audience via Video & even critics changed their opinion of it over those many years to the point it's on the Top 100 Best Films ever made & if you have read the orignal story from book  " Who Goes There " it is very faithful to the book/characters & creatures mentioned within the book & that makes The Thing an even better accomplished movie as that Book was practically at the time just not feasible to do visual effects wise but Rob Bottin & his crew upped their game & took on the challenge & it still stands strong today as when it was first released but if it wasn't for video/laserdisc & then DVD & Blu Ray many films would've been lost in underground vaults somewhere never to be seen & again it comes back to overall content that we get now even with Blu Ray or 4K as it's next to nothing like when Dvds were first released...  I thought it would pick up content wise when Blu Ray came out but nope it's pretty much the same basic next to no extras & if they want sales to continue for DVD/Blu Ray & 4K then distributors need to add all this extra content back in as who is going to buy a basic DVD/Blu Ray film with either No or Next To No Extra Content when they can save their money & wait until it's steamed on some website or Film App...  But alas I think they've made their mind up as many of today's films can been seen for practically nothing but if you entice fans of a film with all the extras put back in like it used to be they will buy it whether it's streamed or not...   In Light of the coronavirus Take Care/Stay Healthy & All The Best...   Ps  Though I will add That it's up to you to make up your own minds: But Don't Believe Everything You See or Hear on the News & so many social media sites... I'm not disputing that there's a virus or something else that's making people ill & worst case scenario is dying but I've never seen the World react to a virus that first discovered in the 1951 & though this strain is immune to antibiotics, something just doesn't smell right as so much of the information given to us contradicts itself & makes no sense when you really think on it...  Again Stay Safe but do not be driven by mass hysteria perpetrated by those in Power/whats said in the News & All Over The Internet...  Do your thinking for yourselves & again Take Care One & All..   .....
